tational name from Parr in Lancashire, or from residence at an enclosure (Middle English <i>parr</i>, Old English <i>pearr</i>).","German: from Middle Low German <i>parre</i> ‘parish, district, minister's house’; a metonymic occupational name for a parson or for someone who worked in a parsonage or manse. Compare   Pfarr  .","English: variant of   Pear   with the common late Middle English and early modern English change of <i>-er</i>- to <i>-ar-</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Pare","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Henri, Laurent, Normand, Fernand, Alphonse, Clermont, Elphege, Alain, Benoit, Gaston, Girard.","French (<b>Paré</b>): occupational name for someone who finished cloth, from the past participle of <i>parer</i> ‘to prepare’.","English: variant of   Parr  ."]},{"name":"Parman","meanings":["Americanized form of German <b>Parmann</b>: variant of   Parr  .","Possibly an altered form of German <b>Bärmann</b> (see   Barmann  ).","English: variant of   Pearman  ."]},{"name":"Porr","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Ulrike, Gunther.","German:","metonymic occupational name for a grower or seller of leeks or other vegetables, from Middle High German <i>porre</i>, <i>pforre</i> ‘leek’ (from Latin <i>porrum</i>)."]},{"name":"Pfarr","meanings":["South German: from Middle High German <i>pfarr</i> ‘district, parish’ or <i>pfarre(r)</i> ‘parish priest’, hence an occupational name for a parson, or a topographic name for someone who lived near the parsonage."]}]},{"name":"Constance","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval form of the Late Latin name <i>Constantia</i>, which is either a feminine derivative of <i>Constans</i> (  see  Constant  ) or an abstract noun meaning ‘constancy’. This was a popular name among the Normans, and was borne by, amongst others, the formidable Constance of Sicily (  1158–98 ), wife of the Emperor  Henry VI ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Phelip","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Greek name <i>Philippos</i>, meaning ‘lover of horses’, from <i>philein</i> ‘to love’ + <i>hippos</i> ‘horse’. This was popular in the classical period and since. It was the name of the father of  Alexander the Great . It was also the name of one of Christ's apostles, of a deacon ordained by the apostles after the death of Christ, and of several other early saints.  See also  Philippa ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":45,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":54,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Constance Phelip Parr was born in 1504, in Exeter, Devon, England. She had at least 1 daughter with Thomas Parry. She died in 1562, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 58."},"et":{"1504–1562":"1504–1562","1500–1580":"1500–1580","1528–1550":"1528–1550","1558":"1558","January 1528":"jaanuar 1528","1500":"1500","January 1550":"jaanuar 1550","1562":"1562","1550":"1550","1580":"1580","1528":"1528","1549":"1549","1504":"1504","Hatfield,